a little over a decade,

00:47:29.260 --> 00:47:35.440
I oversaw a project at Woodrow
Wilson Center that went into--

00:47:35.440 --> 00:47:37.650
systematically went
into the archives

00:47:37.650 --> 00:47:40.670
of North Korea's
former communist allies.

00:47:40.670 --> 00:47:43.930
So some of the countries
that we were in were--

00:47:43.930 --> 00:47:46.390
we were in the Russian
archives, Chinese,

00:47:46.390 --> 00:47:50.530
the East German archives,
Polish, Hungarian, Bulgarian,

00:47:50.530 --> 00:47:56.940
Mongolian, Czech archives
gathering materials that, again,

00:47:56.940 --> 00:48:02.190
are produced in--
largely in North Korea

00:48:02.190 --> 00:48:05.160
and then dispatched back
to Foreign Ministries.

00:48:05.160 --> 00:48:12.890
You have among these materials,
records of conversations

00:48:12.890 --> 00:48:18.260
between North Korean officials
and they're interlocutors

00:48:18.260 --> 00:48:24.740
in North Korea including
for example, the ambassadors

00:48:24.740 --> 00:48:28.770
and also you have working
level diplomats meeting

00:48:28.770 --> 00:48:30.070
with North Korean officials.

00:48:30.070 --> 00:48:33.160
So you have all, you know, many
different levels of meetings.

00:48:33.160 --> 00:48:37.460
You have very high level
meetings between say Kim Il-sung

00:48:37.460 --> 00:48:39.490
and the Soviet Ambassador.

00:48:39.490 --> 00:48:43.150
And then you have-- I
never see councilor meeting

00:48:43.150 --> 00:48:48.640
with somebody talking about the
quality of concrete being used

00:48:48.640 --> 00:48:54.030
to form the foundation
of the newly built annex

00:48:54.030 --> 00:48:59.100
to the Soviet Embassy,
something along those lines.

00:48:59.100 --> 00:49:02.680
So you have many
levels of talks.

00:49:02.680 --> 00:49:07.250
And records are kept for
all of these meetings.

00:49:07.250 --> 00:49:12.300
You also have these diplomatic
cables that are being produced

00:49:12.300 --> 00:49:15.310
in the embassies by
diplomats who are there

00:49:15.310 --> 00:49:19.300
to really observe what's going
on in the country and then

00:49:19.300 --> 00:49:23.940
to report about this and send
these detailed cables back

00:49:23.940 --> 00:49:29.230
to their embassies describing
development in the country,

00:49:29.230 --> 00:49:35.750
developments in their, yeah, in
North Korea's domestic situation

00:49:35.750 --> 00:49:43.660
and as well as North Korea's
relations with their allies.

00:49:43.660 --> 00:49:50.130
These are just the few-- I--
some documents I have sitting

00:49:50.130 --> 00:49:55.080
on the house last night that
I snapped pictures of you have

00:49:55.080 --> 00:49:59.080
for example a-- these are
soviet records from 1954.

00:49:59.080 --> 00:50:04.010
You have for example a record of
conversation with the Ambassador

00:50:04.010 --> 00:50:07.120
of North Korea or the
North Korean Ambassador

00:50:07.120 --> 00:50:10.480
to the Soviet Union, a
guy called [inaudible].

00:50:10.480 --> 00:50:16.130
And then you have a
soviet report on classes

00:50:16.130 --> 00:50:19.680
and class warfare in the DPRK.

00:50:19.680 --> 00:50:26.030
These are-- as you can--
well, this conversation here

00:50:26.030 --> 00:50:31.750
with the Soviet or the
North Korean Ambassador

00:50:31.750 --> 00:50:39.110
to Moscow should add
that we also have records

00:50:39.110 --> 00:50:42.540
of conversations that took
place in other countries, so--

00:50:42.540 --> 00:50:44.570
that involved North
Korean officials.

00:50:44.570 --> 00:50:47.660
So it's not just the
conversations that occurred

00:50:47.660 --> 00:50:52.170
in North Korea but for
example when a meeting occurred

00:50:52.170 --> 00:50:54.180
with the North Korean
Ambassador in Moscow,

00:50:54.180 --> 00:50:55.680
you would have a record of that.

00:50:55.680 --> 00:50:57.940
If a delegation from
North Korea,

00:50:57.940 --> 00:51:00.160
we travel to other countries,

00:51:00.160 --> 00:51:02.350
then you'd also have
the full records

00:51:02.350 --> 00:51:06.070
of those meetings included
in the files from the--

00:51:06.070 --> 00:51:12.450
the files on North Korea
from these archives.

00:51:12.450 --> 00:51:19.330
Some of the things we can
learn about North Korea

00:51:19.330 --> 00:51:21.300
from these materials are--

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:24.330
we can learn a lot about North
Korea's foreign relations,

00:51:24.330 --> 00:51:27.290
a lot about their
domestic politics,

00:51:27.290 --> 00:51:33.580
about economic policies,
military developments and a lot

00:51:33.580 --> 00:51:35.680
about North Korean society.

00:51:35.680 --> 00:51:40.350
There were some limitations as
many of you I'm sure are aware.

00:51:40.350 --> 00:51:43.630
The North Koreans were
not always open even

00:51:43.630 --> 00:51:44.930
to their allies.

00:51:44.930 --> 00:51:48.330
And there were times when
the North Koreans were

00:51:48.330 --> 00:51:50.980
in conflict with their allies.

00:51:50.980 --> 00:51:56.240
So, for example, on the
early 1960s, the relationship

00:51:56.240 --> 00:52:02.320
between Moscow and Pyongyang
soured, and that meant also

00:52:02.320 --> 00:52:07.060
that the relationship between
Pyongyang and most other central

00:52:07.060 --> 00:52:10.790
and eastern European allies
that were closely allied

00:52:10.790 --> 00:52:16.780
with the Soviets
also were not good.

00:52:16.780 --> 00:52:19.270
So in times like this, you know,

00:52:19.270 --> 00:52:22.730
the quality of reporting
could sometimes suffer

00:52:22.730 --> 00:52:24.850
but these diplomats
that were based

00:52:24.850 --> 00:52:27.050
in North Korea were
actually quite skilled

00:52:27.050 --> 00:52:31.390
at gathering information and
would often compared notes.

00:52:31.390 --> 00:52:35.420
And one former East
German Ambassador

00:52:35.420 --> 00:52:38.720
to North Korea described it as
really picking up pebbles here

00:52:38.720 --> 00:52:40.880
and there and then assembling
a mosaic by, you know,

00:52:40.880 --> 00:52:44.280
getting together with, you
know, your friends and,

00:52:44.280 --> 00:52:46.050
you know, comparing notes.

00:52:46.050 --> 00:52:50.910
And you often find among
the records converse--

00:52:50.910 --> 00:52:55.780
records of conversations
between other diplomats

00:52:55.780 --> 00:52:57.120
that are stationed
in North Korea.

00:52:57.120 --> 00:53:00.540
So for example, you
may have a large group.

00:53:00.540 --> 00:53:06.210
You have regular meetings that
occurred between East German,

00:53:06.210 --> 00:53:10.120
Russian, Czech, diplomats where
they would really share notes

00:53:10.120 --> 00:53:17.770
on what they were experiencing
in the country and tried

00:53:17.770 --> 00:53:22.880
to develop a better sense of
developments in the country.

00:53:22.880 --> 00:53:28.380
And this is especially
helpful when the materials

00:53:28.380 --> 00:53:32.370
that the North Koreans
themselves produced don't really

00:53:32.370 --> 00:53:36.470
provide or send a lot
of light on developments

00:53:36.470 --> 00:53:42.270
and political conflict for
example, say 1956 or 1967,

00:53:42.270 --> 00:53:44.910
these are periods
of them working on.

00:53:44.910 --> 00:53:46.960
You don't have a lot of
information about other

00:53:46.960 --> 00:53:51.090
than these reports that
denounce the activities

00:53:51.090 --> 00:53:55.150
of these individuals who
are eventually purged.

00:53:55.150 --> 00:53:58.120
Well we get a better sense by
looking at the conversations

00:53:58.120 --> 00:54:01.520
that these diplomats are
having and then their--

00:54:01.520 --> 00:54:03.650
the cables that they're
producing,

00:54:03.650 --> 00:54:08.980
what was actually going on and
what issue is-- were at stake.

00:54:08.980 --> 00:54:15.450
Was it simply as the standard
narrative, a factional struggle

00:54:15.450 --> 00:54:18.930
or were there principled
policy positions at stake.

00:54:18.930 --> 00:54:22.850
These are things that we can
begin to understand by looking

00:54:22.850 --> 00:54:24.700
at some of these materials.

00:54:24.700 --> 00:54:31.220
So it's a lot of use to
them for the historian.

00:54:31.220 --> 00:54:35.790
They-- Really these materials
force us to step back

00:54:35.790 --> 00:54:37.730
and ask some basic questions,

00:54:37.730 --> 00:54:42.150
basically epistemological
questions about how knowledge

00:54:42.150 --> 00:54:44.370
about North Korea
was-- has been produced

00:54:44.370 --> 00:54:47.300
and how we know what
we think we know.

00:54:47.300 --> 00:54:50.990
And I'm using these to
really challenge a lot

00:54:50.990 --> 00:54:54.320
of things we thought we knew
about North Korean history.

00:54:54.320 --> 00:54:58.540
Things-- I mean is--
I mentioned factions.

00:54:58.540 --> 00:55:06.300
I mean this notion that you
had after the Korean war,

00:55:06.300 --> 00:55:10.580
this intense factional rivalry,
we had-- you had Soviet faction,

00:55:10.580 --> 00:55:12.860
and Chinese faction the
Kim Il-sung's group.

00:55:12.860 --> 00:55:16.110
And Kim Il-sung skillfully
played these factions off one

00:55:16.110 --> 00:55:17.900
another until his
power was unassailable.

00:55:17.900 --> 00:55:19.670
This is the standard narrative.

00:55:19.670 --> 00:55:23.230
What we see if you really
interrogate these materials

00:55:23.230 --> 00:55:25.690
though is that it
wasn't so simple.

00:55:25.690 --> 00:55:29.580
You had, in fact, principled
policy positions at stake.

00:55:29.580 --> 00:55:35.710
And this, these positions seem
to be the issue of contention

00:55:35.710 --> 00:55:38.080
and not so much the
revolutionary background

00:55:38.080 --> 00:55:39.380
of the individuals.

00:55:39.380 --> 00:55:41.040
It was much more complex.

00:55:41.040 --> 00:55:45.550
You have internationalism
versus nationalism.

00:55:45.550 --> 00:55:50.530
You have issues of the
culture personality

00:55:50.530 --> 00:55:52.250
versus collective leadership.

00:55:52.250 --> 00:55:59.300
You have the consumer economy
versus the industrial economy.

00:55:59.300 --> 00:56:01.000
And these, again, are the issues

00:56:01.000 --> 00:56:03.490
that are really driving
political developments

00:56:03.490 --> 00:56:09.070
after the Korean War not just
this notion of, you know,

00:56:09.070 --> 00:56:11.500
endemic factionalism in
the Korean workers party

00:56:11.500 --> 00:56:14.310
that we all know today.

00:56:14.310 --> 00:56:16.230
So, a lot have used
these materials

00:56:16.230 --> 00:56:18.890
to really getting a
better understanding

00:56:18.890 --> 00:56:20.910
of North Korean history

00:56:20.910 --> 00:56:24.380
and rethinking what
we believe we know

00:56:24.380 --> 00:56:26.140
about North Korean history.

00:56:26.140 --> 00:56:30.900
But they-- These materials
also help us understand North

00:56:30.900 --> 00:56:32.370
Korea today.

00:56:32.370 --> 00:56:35.190
But before I get into
that, let me just briefly--

00:56:35.190 --> 00:56:39.830
can I go into where
you can get access

00:56:39.830 --> 00:56:41.130
to a lot of these materials?

00:56:41.130 --> 00:56:44.840
Well, as I said, for a
decade, I ran the project

00:56:44.840 --> 00:56:49.010
at the Wilson Center that
gathered these materials.

00:56:49.010 --> 00:56:51.500
One thing I'm quite proud

00:56:51.500 --> 00:56:55.090
of is something I develop
called the Modern Korean History

00:56:55.090 --> 00:56:58.120
Portal, which provides
multiple points

00:56:58.120 --> 00:56:59.650
of access to the documents.

00:56:59.650 --> 00:57:01.470
And you just go and
then Google and type

00:57:01.470 --> 00:57:03.390
in Modern Korean History Portal.

00:57:03.390 --> 00:57:06.040
And you have, you
know, your timeline

00:57:06.040 --> 00:57:13.310
which just features different
developments in Korean history.

00:57:13.310 --> 00:57:16.140
And you can actually get
direct access to some

00:57:16.140 --> 00:57:17.440
of the relevant documents.

00:57:17.440 --> 00:57:20.240
So, for example, you
know, here's, you know,

00:57:20.240 --> 00:57:25.100
something from September 6,
1945, you have a Soviet report

00:57:25.100 --> 00:57:30.350
on communism in Korea
from that period

00:57:30.350 --> 00:57:32.720
that is directly
relevant connected

00:57:32.720 --> 00:57:36.910
to the issue discussed there.

00:57:36.910 --> 00:57:40.980
You also have featured
resources including essays.

00:57:40.980 --> 00:57:42.400
It's not Wikipedia.

00:57:42.400 --> 00:57:44.480
We're not just letting anyone
write this, but we've--

00:57:44.480 --> 00:57:48.800
you know, when-- actually
commissioned essays

00:57:48.800 --> 00:57:53.490
from professional
scholars of Korean history.

00:57:53.490 --> 00:58:02.790
You also had biographies of key
figures in North Korean history.

00:58:02.790 --> 00:58:06.990
And then you have curated
collections of documents.

00:58:06.990 --> 00:58:10.350
And just, you know, just
click on conversations

00:58:10.350 --> 00:58:12.690
with Kim Il-sung,
you have hundreds

00:58:12.690 --> 00:58:14.570
and hundreds of conversations.

00:58:14.570 --> 00:58:17.670
These records or memorandum
conversations that I was talking

00:58:17.670 --> 00:58:20.640
about with Kim Il-sung going

00:58:20.640 --> 00:58:27.010
from 1949 all the way
through, you see here, 1988.

00:58:27.010 --> 00:58:33.630
It's really spanning this
guy's lifetime in leadership.

00:58:33.630 --> 00:58:37.130
So a great resource.

00:58:37.130 --> 00:58:40.290
I encourage you all to
access it again to work

00:58:40.290 --> 00:58:44.800
with these materials really
challenge your thinking

00:58:44.800 --> 00:58:47.850
about North Korean history.

00:58:47.850 --> 00:58:49.850
But, there's also have
use to these materials

00:58:49.850 --> 00:58:52.540
and really understanding
North Korea today.

00:58:52.540 --> 00:58:57.410
And this requires, you know,
sort of a longer term, you know,

00:58:57.410 --> 00:59:01.020
work with these documents
across, you know,

00:59:01.020 --> 00:59:08.080
larger or a broader
period of time.

00:59:08.080 --> 00:59:10.480
These materials they
also really achieve--

00:59:10.480 --> 00:59:17.500
they really challenge received
wisdom on North Korea today.

00:59:17.500 --> 00:59:22.440
They-- And if you do apply a
broader historical sensibility

00:59:22.440 --> 00:59:26.410
then you can really begin to
identify, you know, patterns

00:59:26.410 --> 00:59:29.590
and really more accurately
interpret

00:59:29.590 --> 00:59:31.650
contemporary developments.

00:59:31.650 --> 00:59:37.230
Let me just look at two
areas where I try to do this.

00:59:37.230 --> 00:59:40.180
So, one thing that's emerged
from these documents, again,

00:59:40.180 --> 00:59:42.630
if you-- when you really
interrogate the materials is

00:59:42.630 --> 00:59:47.670
that we can challenge this idea
that China and North Korean are

00:59:47.670 --> 00:59:50.250
as close as lips and teeth
as the expression goes.

00:59:50.250 --> 00:59:51.860
This expression is
suggesting, of course,

00:59:51.860 --> 00:59:55.810
the level of intimacy
among two states.

00:59:55.810 --> 01:00:01.310
And that Beijing today
wields enormous influence

01:00:01.310 --> 01:00:03.030
over Pyongyang.

01:00:03.030 --> 01:00:04.360
What you can see
from the materials

01:00:04.360 --> 01:00:06.790
and then I encourage you to
look through these conversations

01:00:06.790 --> 01:00:10.750
with Kim Il-sung in particular,
you can see that, well,

01:00:10.750 --> 01:00:15.800
this may not be the case that in
fact there is a profound sense

01:00:15.800 --> 01:00:20.280
of mistrust in the relationship,
really going both ways.

01:00:20.280 --> 01:00:22.150
But for the North Koreans,

01:00:22.150 --> 01:00:25.590
one can see from the
conversations not just

01:00:25.590 --> 01:00:28.020
with Kim Il-sung but with
many other I mentioned

01:00:28.020 --> 01:00:31.290
that you have conversations
at various levels.

01:00:31.290 --> 01:00:33.300
At all levels, you see people,

01:00:33.300 --> 01:00:36.820
North Korean officials
describing this profound sense

01:00:36.820 --> 01:00:43.450
of mistrust toward Beijing, this
sense that China is, at times,

01:00:43.450 --> 01:00:46.220
overly interventionist
and not respectful

01:00:46.220 --> 01:00:48.000
of Korean sovereignty.

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:50.650
And what's fascinating is
to look at conversations

01:00:50.650 --> 01:00:52.680
with Kim Il-sung and to see how

01:00:52.680 --> 01:00:57.170
over the years the list
of grievances grows.

01:00:57.170 --> 01:01:00.570
So, in 1955, you
see him complaining

01:01:00.570 --> 01:01:06.890
about the actions
of, for example,

01:01:06.890 --> 01:01:10.950
[inaudible] during the Korean
War that person who was

01:01:10.950 --> 01:01:13.890
in charge with the Chinese
people's volunteers.

01:01:13.890 --> 01:01:17.640
His arrogance and
dealing with Kim Il-sung

01:01:17.640 --> 01:01:20.170
and he also blames
[inaudible] for decisions--

01:01:20.170 --> 01:01:26.160
battlefield decisions that
Kim felt ultimately caused

01:01:26.160 --> 01:01:27.460
him victory.

01:01:27.460 --> 01:01:31.360
A couple years later,
you see him adding on to

01:01:31.360 --> 01:01:36.950
that list describing events
in 1956 where the Chinese

01:01:36.950 --> 01:01:40.280
and the soviets directly
meddled in,

01:01:40.280 --> 01:01:43.650
you know, in a party conflict.

01:01:43.650 --> 01:01:46.310
You see then this list
growing and growing

01:01:46.310 --> 01:01:47.610
and growing over the years.

01:01:47.610 --> 01:01:50.170
So you have the cultural
revolutions.

01:01:50.170 --> 01:01:54.540
You have eventually
even the criticism

01:01:54.540 --> 01:01:57.170
of Kim Jong-Il's succession.

01:01:57.170 --> 01:02:04.690
But it mixed clear that there
is a profound sense of mistrust.

01:02:04.690 --> 01:02:08.410
And this really forces us to
question this understanding

01:02:08.410 --> 01:02:11.610
that we have today that,
you know, basically the road

01:02:11.610 --> 01:02:14.820
to Pyongyang starts in Beijing
and that we really need--

01:02:14.820 --> 01:02:16.310
And then China, you know,

01:02:16.310 --> 01:02:21.490
again wields enormous political
influence over North Korea.

01:02:21.490 --> 01:02:26.430
Clearly, yes, they wield
enormous material leverage

01:02:26.430 --> 01:02:31.390
but what we can learn from-- you
know, by through the application

01:02:31.390 --> 01:02:35.220
of a broader historical
sensibility using these

01:02:35.220 --> 01:02:36.910
documents, we can understand

01:02:36.910 --> 01:02:39.690
that China does not
have the ability

01:02:39.690 --> 01:02:42.740
to act will exercise
political influence

01:02:42.740 --> 01:02:45.280
because of this really
tortured history.

01:02:45.280 --> 01:02:50.480
Another area where--
again, we all--

01:02:50.480 --> 01:02:52.280
you know, again the
received wisdom is

01:02:52.280 --> 01:02:55.870
that the North Koreans
skillfully played the Soviets

01:02:55.870 --> 01:03:00.430
and the Chinese off one
another throughout the Cold War

01:03:00.430 --> 01:03:01.730
that there were these--

01:03:01.730 --> 01:03:04.270
you know, Kim Il-sung was
this master manipulator.

01:03:04.270 --> 01:03:07.220
And he was able to
extract maximum concessions

01:03:07.220 --> 01:03:10.220
from the soviets
and the Chinese.

01:03:10.220 --> 01:03:14.330
This I actually think is an
extension of this understanding

01:03:14.330 --> 01:03:16.390
that we have about
factional rivalry

01:03:16.390 --> 01:03:18.550
within the Korean workers party

01:03:18.550 --> 01:03:21.780
where Kim skillfully played the
rival factions off one another

01:03:21.780 --> 01:03:23.210
until his power was
unassailable.

01:03:23.210 --> 01:03:25.660
And this, I would say, goes back

01:03:25.660 --> 01:03:29.100
to Japanese colonial
era propaganda

01:03:29.100 --> 01:03:32.550
of this essentialist narrative
of endemic factionalism.

01:03:32.550 --> 01:03:37.180
But Kim Il-sung certainly
uses this

01:03:37.180 --> 01:03:41.890
and labels his rivals
as factions.

01:03:41.890 --> 01:03:48.040
But we have this
understanding that Kim was able

01:03:48.040 --> 01:03:50.920
to play others off one
another and, again,

01:03:50.920 --> 01:03:52.870
extract maximum concessions.

01:03:52.870 --> 01:03:56.080
But when you really look at
when you break down the--

01:03:56.080 --> 01:04:01.810
you know, if you look--
really examine his--

01:04:01.810 --> 01:04:06.190
the relationship between the
soviets and the North Koreans

01:04:06.190 --> 01:04:09.990
and the Chinese and the
north Koreans over the years,

01:04:09.990 --> 01:04:14.910
you see that North Korea never
really has sufficient leverage

01:04:14.910 --> 01:04:20.290
over either Moscow or Beijing to
really extract these concessions

01:04:20.290 --> 01:04:21.590
that we all think that they got.

01:04:21.590 --> 01:04:25.770
And in fact what they did
receive was often stuff

01:04:25.770 --> 01:04:28.820
that the soviets themselves were
no longer even using or things

01:04:28.820 --> 01:04:30.770
that the-- or the
Chinese couldn't--

01:04:30.770 --> 01:04:33.650
weren't actually producing
things that were helpful

01:04:33.650 --> 01:04:37.750
to the North Koreans or
at least at the level

01:04:37.750 --> 01:04:41.200
that the North Koreans
had hoped.

01:04:41.200 --> 01:04:45.400
Moreover when relations
were poor with the soviets,

01:04:45.400 --> 01:04:51.150
for example, from '62 to
'64, it's a very short period

01:04:51.150 --> 01:04:53.330
of time, they were so poor

01:04:53.330 --> 01:04:55.540
that the North Koreans
had really no choice

01:04:55.540 --> 01:04:59.070
but to move closer to
the Chinese, otherwise,

01:04:59.070 --> 01:05:01.490
they would have been
completely isolated.

01:05:01.490 --> 01:05:04.720
Likewise when relations
report with the Chinese,

01:05:04.720 --> 01:05:07.800
this is during the culture
evolution, they were so poor.

01:05:07.800 --> 01:05:11.780
I mean to the point where you
had armed clashes on the border.

01:05:11.780 --> 01:05:14.050
You know, Chinese
troops marching

01:05:14.050 --> 01:05:17.850
into North Korean territory.

01:05:17.850 --> 01:05:21.210
Then, you know, North Korea
really didn't have any choice

01:05:21.210 --> 01:05:24.340
but to warm up to the Soviets.

01:05:24.340 --> 01:05:27.200
Again, they would have been
completely isolated had

01:05:27.200 --> 01:05:28.510
they not.

01:05:28.510 --> 01:05:32.230
The North Koreans were more
reactive than they were,

01:05:32.230 --> 01:05:34.630
you know, the master
manipulators, you know,

01:05:34.630 --> 01:05:39.540
sort of juggling all
these balls at one time.

01:05:39.540 --> 01:05:43.170
And indeed by the '70s, by--

01:05:43.170 --> 01:05:46.640
as the more extreme faces of the
Cultural Revolution subsided,

01:05:46.640 --> 01:05:51.510
the North Koreans took
steps to really reduce

01:05:51.510 --> 01:05:54.600
to the extent possible, the
influence of both Beijing

01:05:54.600 --> 01:05:57.720
and Moscow on a trajectory
of political economic

01:05:57.720 --> 01:05:59.060
and cultural developments.

01:05:59.060 --> 01:06:01.740
This is something they
started early but really tried

01:06:01.740 --> 01:06:05.690
to make the country
impervious to these influences

01:06:05.690 --> 01:06:10.440
and maintains a policy of
equidistance, you know,

01:06:10.440 --> 01:06:14.550
keeping both Moscow and
Beijing at arms length.

01:06:14.550 --> 01:06:19.920
