community would not waste their

01:20:43.580 --> 01:20:48.590
time reading 13 pages
even though I think it's--

01:20:48.590 --> 01:20:50.650
they would learn much from it.

01:20:50.650 --> 01:20:52.210
So, you know, just kind

01:20:52.210 --> 01:20:54.300
of extract the most
important parts of it.

01:20:54.300 --> 01:20:59.280
And, you know, you cannot put
them in a brief report and try

01:20:59.280 --> 01:21:01.550
to get that in their hands.

01:21:01.550 --> 01:21:06.450
I've had the opportunity to
brief people just, you know,

01:21:06.450 --> 01:21:09.060
across the street
here, members of--

01:21:09.060 --> 01:21:12.930
it's actually senators
and member of the house.

01:21:12.930 --> 01:21:17.490
And I don't know that they
actually look at them,

01:21:17.490 --> 01:21:22.160
they'll listen to me as I'm
describing the contents, but,

01:21:22.160 --> 01:21:24.870
you know, I don't know if they
take the time to read the two

01:21:24.870 --> 01:21:26.740
or three page summary
and, you know,

01:21:26.740 --> 01:21:31.270
extracts or excerpts rather.

01:21:31.270 --> 01:21:34.470
But, you know, there's so
much that you could do.

01:21:34.470 --> 01:21:39.640
You know, you can't compile
all of these rich, you know,

01:21:39.640 --> 01:21:43.620
materials and do a
two-paragraph summary.

01:21:43.620 --> 01:21:49.140
I mean you can, but, you know,
as a historian, of course,

01:21:49.140 --> 01:21:53.110
I tend toward, you know,
I want to, you know,

01:21:53.110 --> 01:21:55.050
give the full context, you know.

01:21:55.050 --> 01:21:57.590
So there are challenges and--

01:21:57.590 --> 01:22:01.640
but, you know, certainly
the material is there.

01:22:01.640 --> 01:22:05.940
There are efforts to, you
know, curate collections

01:22:05.940 --> 01:22:09.580
to make it more accessible to--

01:22:09.580 --> 01:22:13.780
you know, and then to
compile these forts,

01:22:13.780 --> 01:22:19.810
but one thing I find with North
Korea is that people are just--

01:22:19.810 --> 01:22:23.890
you know, you have your
fixed ideas and, you know,

01:22:23.890 --> 01:22:28.720
no matter how many documents
I waive in front of your face,

01:22:28.720 --> 01:22:31.930
you're not going to
change your mind.

01:22:31.930 --> 01:22:34.600
That's something that's
frustrating us, you know,

01:22:34.600 --> 01:22:37.950
as a historian who's been
setting the country for,

01:22:37.950 --> 01:22:41.010
you know, a long time now, and
who really understand that much

01:22:41.010 --> 01:22:46.680
of what we think we know
is-- has been, you know,

01:22:46.680 --> 01:22:50.740
needs to be reconsidered.

01:22:50.740 --> 01:22:55.270
But, with North Korea, because
there is this perception,

01:22:55.270 --> 01:22:58.360
you know, again, the black
box or there's, you know,

01:22:58.360 --> 01:23:01.600
this notion that North Korea
is unknown and unknowable,

01:23:01.600 --> 01:23:07.760
people just don't want
to challenge these--

01:23:07.760 --> 01:23:10.950
you know, what they bring to
the table already, these notions

01:23:10.950 --> 01:23:15.990
that they already have,
so frustrating but--

