01:26:16.140 --> 01:26:17.940
&gt;&gt; Daniel Wertz: Jonathan?

01:26:17.940 --> 01:26:36.820
[ Inaudible ]

01:26:36.820 --> 01:26:38.120
&gt;&gt; James F. Person: Sure.

01:26:38.120 --> 01:26:44.590
So after the Korean War,
you had this debate within--

01:26:44.590 --> 01:26:46.340
well, you had a discussion.

01:26:46.340 --> 01:26:53.690
You had-- you know, it was a
very diverse party at that time,

01:26:53.690 --> 01:26:54.990
you did have people

01:26:54.990 --> 01:27:01.330
with different revolutionary
backgrounds, but-- and they--

01:27:01.330 --> 01:27:03.560
you know, and you had some
that were more internationals

01:27:03.560 --> 01:27:06.820
than more in-tuned with what was
happening in the socialist camp.

01:27:06.820 --> 01:27:10.190
And after the death of Joseph
Stalin, you had a reorientation

01:27:10.190 --> 01:27:14.060
of the Soviet economy toward
consumer goods, you know,

01:27:14.060 --> 01:27:17.860
sort of the-- shifting from
the industrial economy to more,

01:27:17.860 --> 01:27:21.740
you know, geared toward
improving the living standards

01:27:21.740 --> 01:27:23.040
for the Soviet citizen.

01:27:23.040 --> 01:27:27.790
This was then promoted
throughout the socialist camp

01:27:27.790 --> 01:27:29.090
including to North Korea.

01:27:29.090 --> 01:27:33.270
And in fact, these new Soviet
policies were reflected

01:27:33.270 --> 01:27:37.360
in Soviet aid to North Korea.

01:27:37.360 --> 01:27:45.510
We're only-- all but 3% of the
total amount of aid was given

01:27:45.510 --> 01:27:50.990
as a blank check, everything
else was allocated for projects

01:27:50.990 --> 01:27:54.340
that essentially-- that
would have, in some way,

01:27:54.340 --> 01:28:00.590
improve the living standards
of the North Korean people.

01:28:00.590 --> 01:28:03.560
Kim Il-sung, however,
was really trying

01:28:03.560 --> 01:28:06.000
to eliminate colonial
error distortions

01:28:06.000 --> 01:28:07.580
to the national economy.

01:28:07.580 --> 01:28:10.880
It was determined
to make an economy

01:28:10.880 --> 01:28:14.240
that was more internally
interdependent

01:28:14.240 --> 01:28:18.440
and externally independent
wanting

01:28:18.440 --> 01:28:24.100
to eliminate the potential for
future dependency relationships.

01:28:24.100 --> 01:28:27.260
After the Korean War,
he saw that the--

01:28:27.260 --> 01:28:33.070
they were utterly dependent
on the Soviets especially

01:28:33.070 --> 01:28:34.530
for military and so, he--

01:28:34.530 --> 01:28:39.960
and as the basis for
developing an economy

01:28:39.960 --> 01:28:41.520
or developing military,

01:28:41.520 --> 01:28:44.590
you needed to have an
industrial economy.

01:28:44.590 --> 01:28:52.650
And so, Kim was focused on
general industrialization

01:28:52.650 --> 01:28:54.750
but focusing on heavy industry.

01:28:54.750 --> 01:29:00.100
Wanted to, again, to eliminate
these colonial-era distortions

01:29:00.100 --> 01:29:03.360
where you had highly
developed extractive

01:29:03.360 --> 01:29:06.490
and primary processing
industries, but no ability

01:29:06.490 --> 01:29:09.080
to produce spare parts
and finished goods.

01:29:09.080 --> 01:29:14.410
So you had then this-- you
had discussion in the party

01:29:14.410 --> 01:29:16.850
over which path to take.

01:29:16.850 --> 01:29:20.800
Do you follow the Soviet model
and improve living conditions?

01:29:20.800 --> 01:29:22.860
And the more internationalist
member

01:29:22.860 --> 01:29:26.600
of the Korean workers party
were supportive of this,

01:29:26.600 --> 01:29:29.550
but Kim Il-sung was
very much focused

01:29:29.550 --> 01:29:33.380
on eliminating future
dependency relations,

01:29:33.380 --> 01:29:40.130
including with allies, the
Soviet Union and China.

01:29:40.130 --> 01:29:45.680
And you have then this
discussion in the party turning

01:29:45.680 --> 01:29:53.190
into a debate when you have a
famine in late '54, early '55.

01:29:53.190 --> 01:29:56.070
And there's a lot of
criticism of Kim's policies

01:29:56.070 --> 01:29:57.740
which are focused so much on--

01:29:57.740 --> 01:30:06.140
despite the fact that Soviet
aid is not supporting his plans.

01:30:06.140 --> 01:30:10.310
He is mobilizing indigenous
human immaterial resources

01:30:10.310 --> 01:30:14.050
to try to push through
his goals.

01:30:14.050 --> 01:30:19.370
But then you have this famine
that comes with the process

01:30:19.370 --> 01:30:22.380
of collectivizing agriculture.

01:30:22.380 --> 01:30:28.370
And this discussion
turns more into criticism

01:30:28.370 --> 01:30:30.730
and there are unfavorable
comparisons being made

01:30:30.730 --> 01:30:35.550
between Kim's policies and
the policies being implemented

01:30:35.550 --> 01:30:39.010
in the Soviet Union to
improve living conditions.

01:30:39.010 --> 01:30:45.530
And at that point, Kim Il-sung
begins to see this as a threat.

01:30:45.530 --> 01:30:48.700
It's more-- He sees as a threat.

01:30:48.700 --> 01:30:51.310
It was national security
imperatives

01:30:51.310 --> 01:30:53.820
and as a challenge
to him personally.

01:30:53.820 --> 01:30:55.640
He didn't see this
debate as something

01:30:55.640 --> 01:30:59.360
that would necessarily
strengthen policy but he saw it

01:30:59.360 --> 01:31:03.400
as a direct challenge.

01:31:03.400 --> 01:31:08.370
And so, this is when he begins
this process of othering.

01:31:08.370 --> 01:31:11.210
In focusing on the revolutionary
backgrounds of the people

01:31:11.210 --> 01:31:14.400
who were more cosmopolitan
who were more internationalist

01:31:14.400 --> 01:31:20.980
and were advancing or
promoting the adaption

01:31:20.980 --> 01:31:23.720
of Soviet economic policies.

01:31:23.720 --> 01:31:27.360
And at the same time, he
is promoting his own--

01:31:27.360 --> 01:31:29.620
highlighting his own
revolutionary background

01:31:29.620 --> 01:31:33.280
as the core of the Korean
revolutionary tradition.

01:31:33.280 --> 01:31:39.000
So he's marginalizing those who
are criticizing his policies

01:31:39.000 --> 01:31:42.450
and engineering their downfall.

01:31:42.450 --> 01:31:50.000
But what-- I mean, we can see
a lot about this from a lot

01:31:50.000 --> 01:31:58.250
of the Soviet reports after
'55 in particular, but you have

01:31:58.250 --> 01:32:02.910
to also compare with-- you
have to look also to fill it

01:32:02.910 --> 01:32:04.620
out a little bit
because it's not--

01:32:04.620 --> 01:32:06.180
the level of reporting
immediately

01:32:06.180 --> 01:32:08.180
after the Korean
War is not so great

01:32:08.180 --> 01:32:10.240
because the embassies
were just rebuilding.

01:32:10.240 --> 01:32:12.660
They were just moving
back to Pyongyang.

01:32:12.660 --> 01:32:15.400
And so, for example, the Soviet
Embassy wasn't even rebuilt yet,

01:32:15.400 --> 01:32:17.370
they were operating out
of temporary facilities.

01:32:17.370 --> 01:32:19.850
They weren't-- the embassy
was not fully staffed,

01:32:19.850 --> 01:32:22.460
there were other embassies.

01:32:22.460 --> 01:32:26.560
So you have to look at
the available reports

01:32:26.560 --> 01:32:29.270
and then come here to
the Library of Congress

01:32:29.270 --> 01:32:32.990
and read North Korea's own
publication, the periodicals.

01:32:32.990 --> 01:32:35.500
For example, I was just,
before you all arrived,

01:32:35.500 --> 01:32:37.950
I was over there
looking at [inaudible],

01:32:37.950 --> 01:32:42.670
which is the party's--
it's the-- [Inaudible].

01:32:42.670 --> 01:32:43.970
Hmm? [Inaudible].

01:32:43.970 --> 01:32:50.860
No, I'm describing what it is.

01:32:50.860 --> 01:32:54.090
It's a journal that's produced
by the Central Committee.

01:32:54.090 --> 01:32:57.720
So it's the party's
official journal.

01:32:57.720 --> 01:32:59.080
And you can see actually--

01:32:59.080 --> 01:33:04.230
in [inaudible], you can
actually see the saddle

01:33:04.230 --> 01:33:09.510
of these debates occurring
in-- among top officials.

01:33:09.510 --> 01:33:10.810
But they're very subtle.

01:33:10.810 --> 01:33:13.240
I mean it's not-- you're not
going to see overt criticism

01:33:13.240 --> 01:33:16.430
of Kim and of his
policies in these journals.

01:33:16.430 --> 01:33:20.140
They're just sort of,
well, you know, you have--

01:33:20.140 --> 01:33:22.710
on the one side,
you have, you know,

01:33:22.710 --> 01:33:24.990
the industrial economy
is the basis

01:33:24.990 --> 01:33:28.470
of an independent
national economy.

01:33:28.470 --> 01:33:31.740
And after you have an
industrial North Korea,

01:33:31.740 --> 01:33:34.860
then you can have
improved living conditions

01:33:34.860 --> 01:33:38.240
and we will have an
independent military as well.

01:33:38.240 --> 01:33:41.480
And then on the other side you
see sort of these discussions

01:33:41.480 --> 01:33:44.090
that we're promoting
an improvement

01:33:44.090 --> 01:33:46.140
of a living conditions, you
know, the people have suffered

01:33:46.140 --> 01:33:50.020
over throughout the
colonial era and then from--

01:33:50.020 --> 01:33:52.960
after the devastation

01:33:52.960 --> 01:33:55.360
of the [inaudible] the
American Imperialist aggressors.

01:33:55.360 --> 01:33:57.320
You know it's time
to really focus

01:33:57.320 --> 01:33:59.150
on improving living
conditions for the people.

01:33:59.150 --> 01:34:03.960
And so you see these subtle
discussions in these journals.

01:34:03.960 --> 01:34:07.550
And then again when you compare
that then with what you have

01:34:07.550 --> 01:34:11.890
from the Soviet records and East
German record, then, you know,

01:34:11.890 --> 01:34:14.650
forward picture emerges.

01:34:14.650 --> 01:34:18.050
If you people have really tried
to look at this period though

01:34:18.050 --> 01:34:20.680
or if you contextualized
some of the developments

01:34:20.680 --> 01:34:26.910
that occurred during this period
including Kim Il-sung's use

01:34:26.910 --> 01:34:31.530
of the expression Juche,
this is something--

01:34:31.530 --> 01:34:33.830
you'll have to wait
my book, yeah.

