01:36:30.900 --> 01:36:33.710
like really first, I thought
there's a committee there but,

01:36:33.710 --> 01:36:38.720
you know, really commixing
comedy and then crown,

01:36:38.720 --> 01:36:40.380
you know, you never know.

01:36:40.380 --> 01:36:43.760
So it's like a really
playground, you have to come in

01:36:43.760 --> 01:36:46.800
and play around to
find out what we have.

01:36:46.800 --> 01:36:48.100
&gt;&gt; Daniel Wertz: And a lot of--

01:36:48.100 --> 01:36:51.110
Are these materials made
available to the public shortly

01:36:51.110 --> 01:36:53.480
after the library receives them?

01:36:53.480 --> 01:36:54.780
&gt;&gt; Sonya Lee: Yes.

01:36:54.780 --> 01:36:58.750
But anything, you know, coming
to the library takes at least--

01:36:58.750 --> 01:37:02.280
average of five or six
months to finish its logging

01:37:02.280 --> 01:37:05.790
and then finish binding
some cases and then--

01:37:05.790 --> 01:37:09.950
so it takes a while but still--
so if you look at the record,

01:37:09.950 --> 01:37:15.580
for example, we have until--
[inaudible] 2017 December

01:37:15.580 --> 01:37:16.880
and then I get occasion.

01:37:16.880 --> 01:37:18.190
That means you don't
have after that,

01:37:18.190 --> 01:37:20.470
of course [inaudible]
keep getting it.

01:37:20.470 --> 01:37:21.770
&gt;&gt; Daniel Wertz: Yeah.

01:37:21.770 --> 01:37:24.060
&gt;&gt; Sonya Lee: But still we
have only available like 2017

01:37:24.060 --> 01:37:26.360
and we-- Yeah, so
it take some time.

01:37:26.360 --> 01:37:28.210
&gt;&gt; Daniel Wertz: And for those
more contemporary records,

01:37:28.210 --> 01:37:30.310
are there audiovisual materials

01:37:30.310 --> 01:37:33.050
in North Korean movies,
music, et cetera?

01:37:33.050 --> 01:37:35.460
Or does it tend to
be more textual?

01:37:35.460 --> 01:37:37.280
&gt;&gt; Sonya Lee: The
Asian Division,

01:37:37.280 --> 01:37:41.000
we collect the printing
material mostly.

01:37:41.000 --> 01:37:42.300
&gt;&gt; Daniel Wertz: OK.

01:37:42.300 --> 01:37:43.600
&gt;&gt; Sonya Lee: Because we
don't have any facility

01:37:43.600 --> 01:37:47.270
to play the music or soundtrack.

01:37:47.270 --> 01:37:51.520
I recommend a few titles
every year from North Korea

01:37:51.520 --> 01:37:56.710
but this is not Asian
Division position, you know,

01:37:56.710 --> 01:38:00.820
it's in the motion picture
in a special format.

01:38:00.820 --> 01:38:03.590
So not really-- not
that many though.

01:38:05.890 --> 01:38:07.750
&gt;&gt; James F. Person: There's-- By
the way, there's a great article

01:38:07.750 --> 01:38:09.260
that came out by Andre Schmid.

01:38:09.260 --> 01:38:13.360
I think it was in-- was it the
journal of Asian studies or--

01:38:13.360 --> 01:38:18.540
just a couple of months
ago that describes work

01:38:18.540 --> 01:38:24.460
with these materials at
the Library of Congress.

01:38:24.460 --> 01:38:25.880
He's at University of Toronto.

01:38:25.880 --> 01:38:29.230
He actually has a book
that's coming out, I think,

01:38:29.230 --> 01:38:34.670
later this year or next
year, so probably next year.

01:38:34.670 --> 01:38:39.750
But that really just uses these
materials to get it, you know,

01:38:39.750 --> 01:38:41.160
everyday life in North Korea.

01:38:41.160 --> 01:38:42.780
In fact, there have been a
number of works that have come

01:38:42.780 --> 01:38:45.890
out in recent years, again,
Everyday Life in North Korea,

01:38:45.890 --> 01:38:48.850
Susie Kim's book on '45
to '50, which uses a lot

01:38:48.850 --> 01:38:53.920
of the materials at the Library
of Congress, I'm sorry, at NARA,

01:38:53.920 --> 01:38:57.880
at the National Archives.

01:38:57.880 --> 01:39:02.230
Harrison or Cheehyung
Harrison Kim at the University

01:39:02.230 --> 01:39:05.630
of Hawaii has a book
coming out in October.

01:39:05.630 --> 01:39:10.590
That is about Workers-- it's
called "Workers and Toilers",

01:39:10.590 --> 01:39:12.710
that also uses a
lot of materials

01:39:12.710 --> 01:39:18.980
from the caption
records, and I think a lot

01:39:18.980 --> 01:39:21.530
from the LOC materials.

01:39:21.530 --> 01:39:23.940
But this is also
looking everyday life

01:39:23.940 --> 01:39:26.500
of the worker after--

01:39:26.500 --> 01:39:32.060
but focuses particularly on
the post-Korean War period, OK.

01:39:32.060 --> 01:39:33.390
&gt;&gt; Daniel Wertz: So it sounds
